            <fr:display-uri>008G</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/lectures/008G/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Atomic sentences">Atomic sentences</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>    These valuations on a frame start from assigning values to atomic formulas, and then on this basis we can calculate the values assigned to compound formulas.
    We do this by assigning to each point in the frame some <html:em>set</html:em> of atomic formulas, to be understood as the set of atomic formulas that get the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> at that point.
</html:p>
            <html:p>    But unlike when we're dealing with valuations on structures, here the assignment of values to atomic formulas is not completely unconstrained.
    Recall the knowledge interpretation: when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x R y]]></fr:tex> in a frame, we want that to mean that we can move from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> without losing any knowledge that's present at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex>.
    So our valuations are constrained in this way: if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(p, x) = Y]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x R y]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>, then we must have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M(p, y) = Y]]></fr:tex> as well.
    That goes for any atomic sentence, not just <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.
    In other words, when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x R y]]></fr:tex> in a frame, then the set of atomic formulas a valuation assigns to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> must be a <html:em>subset</html:em> of the set it assigns to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
