                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/008H/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>008H</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/008H/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Valuation on a frame">Valuation on a frame</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A <html:strong>valuation on a frame</html:strong> is a choice of a set of atomic sentences for each point in the frame, subject to the condition that for all points <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x, y]]></fr:tex> in the frame, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x R y]]></fr:tex>, then the set assigned to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> must be a subset of the set assigned to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>    For an example, return to Example frame 1.
    Let's assign sets of atomics to points as follows: 1 gets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q\}]]></fr:tex>; 2 gets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q, r\}]]></fr:tex>; 3 gets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{p, q, r\}]]></fr:tex>; and 4 gets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{q, s\}]]></fr:tex>.
    This meets our requirement: whenever one point is reachable from another in this frame, the point we're reaching from gets a subset of the set assigned to the point we're reaching to.
    Note as well that when we have a loop of reachability, like between 2 and 3 in this frame, then that means that every point in the loop must be assigned the very same set of atomics.
</html:p>
            <html:p>    In this model, I've assigned only a finite set of atomics to each point.
    But this is not required at all; any choice of sets of atomics is a valuation, so long as it connects to reachability in the required way.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
